---
// /crowds — the deep "how it works" layer for Crowd Intelligence, and the
// landing page for the app's explainer sheet link ("How we do the wizardry →",
// CrowdExplainerSheet.swift — that URL is a RELEASE GATE for the 1.2 un-gate:
// this page must be live on lanyardpass.com before the sheet ships un-gated).
//
// 1.2 GATE — FLIPPED 2026-07-18 (staged on plant-street with the 1.2.1
// submission; live when the branch promotes): noindex removed + sitemap
// exclusion dropped (astro.config.mjs). The /details hub's live chapter card
// landed earlier with details-launch. Page is now fully public at promotion.
//
// Voice contract: this page deepens CrowdExplainerSheet's ten Q&As — same
// facts, one register down. If the sheet's copy changes, re-read this page.
// Public-safe boundary: mechanism at the level the sheet already ships
// (wait times every 15 min, two years of own history, own-curve grading).
// The recipe (index formula, percentile cuts, threshold windows) stays out.
//
// GROWTH CONTRACT (Dan, 2026-07-16): this is the ONE crowd page, forever —
// the app links this URL from shipped binaries, so it never fragments into
// per-version pages. Each shipped phase (v2 nowcast, v3 crowd calendar,
// v4 best bet) graduates from "The road ahead" into its own section here,
// the same release the phase ships — mirroring the explainer sheet's
// one-new-question-per-phase rule. Teasing unshipped phases is deliberate:
// we ship (1.0, 1.1, and Crowd Intelligence inside one summer), so the
// roadmap is a promise we have a record of keeping.
import DetailLayout from '@/layouts/DetailLayout.astro';
import CrowdPlaza from '@/components/details/CrowdPlaza.astro';
import { SITE } from '@/data/site';

export const prerender = true;

const title = `How we do the wizardry | ${SITE.name}`;
const description =
  'How Lanyard reads a park. One honest word, Quiet, Normal, or Packed, graded against that park\'s own history — and silence whenever the data isn\'t sure.';
---
<DetailLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  heroKicker="The details · Crowd Intelligence"
  heroTitle="How we do the wizardry."
  heroSub="Your park card carries a one-word crowd report. Quiet, Normal, or Packed, judged the only fair way, against that park's own history. The card keeps it to one word. This page is the rest of the story."
>
  <section class="chapter">
    <p class="chapter__kicker">The window</p>
    <h2>The card shows you the park, not a chart</h2>
    <p>
      When a park is packed, the little figures on your card, the Parkfolk, gather at the gates.
      On a quiet Tuesday night it might be two souls under the moon. There's a family with a
      stroller, a kid riding shoulders, and somewhere in the crowd, a balloon that now and then
      gets away.
    </p>
    <p>
      The Parkfolk aren't decoration. Their numbers track the real reading, so the scene and the
      word always agree. The scene expresses. The word asserts. And the word never lets the charm
      carry a fact by itself.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="chapter">
    <p class="chapter__kicker">Try it</p>
    <h2>Drive the plaza yourself</h2>
    <p>
      This is the language the card speaks, in miniature. Set the word and watch the plaza answer,
      arrivals and departures included.
    </p>
    <CrowdPlaza />
  </section>

  <section class="chapter">
    <p class="chapter__kicker">The math</p>
    <h2>How it knows</h2>
    <p>
      Lanyard reads posted wait times every fifteen minutes and weighs the moment against roughly
      two years of that park's own history, matched to the right time of day, because a 9am
      reading judged against a mid-afternoon standard would flatter every morning.
    </p>
    <p>
      Every park is graded on its own curve. Packed means packed for that park. A slammed day at
      SeaWorld and a slammed day at Epic Universe are wildly different wait times, and pretending
      one scale fits every gate is how other apps end up wrong politely. Behind the grading sits
      more than ten thousand recorded park-days, and before a park earned its words, the math had
      to prove itself on days it had never seen.
    </p>
    <p>
      One more thing the evidence settled. Same-day weather barely moves a park's crowd level.
      Rain redistributes a day, it doesn't re-level it. So weather stays on your card as weather,
      and the crowd word stays about the crowd.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="chapter">
    <p class="chapter__kicker">The words</p>
    <h2>Three honest words, no fake-precise number</h2>
    <p>
      There is no crowd score in Lanyard, no 6 out of 10, and that's on purpose. We can stand
      behind Quiet, Normal, and Packed. Nobody on earth can stand behind the difference between
      a 6 and a 7, and an app that pretends otherwise is decorating a guess.
    </p>
    <p>
      It's an observation, not a prediction. The word describes what the lines look like right
      now, and it can change through the day, which is exactly what you want from a park that
      fluctuates.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="chapter">
    <p class="chapter__kicker">The silence</p>
    <h2>When it says nothing, that's the feature working</h2>
    <p>
      Some mornings the word takes a few minutes to appear, because wait times need a moment to
      settle after open and we don't like to guess. If the data goes stale, the word disappears
      rather than coast on old information. New parks and seasonal parks are still earning their
      measuring stick, so they stay quiet until their history is deep enough to grade fairly.
    </p>
    <p>
      The deal is simple. If there's a word on the card, we stand behind it. If we can't stand
      behind it, there's no word.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="chapter">
    <p class="chapter__kicker">The road ahead</p>
    <h2>Where the wizardry goes next</h2>
    <p>
      What's in the app today is the honest observer. It's also the foundation, and the same
      evidence base that graded the parks has already mapped the next three moves.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>The morning tells you the day.</strong> A park's first hour of wait times
        predicts its afternoon remarkably well. Next up is a morning read on where today is
        heading, so "should I go today?" gets an answer before you're in the car.</li>
      <li><strong>Crowd words on the calendar.</strong> After that, the ninety-day calendar
        learns the words, fused with your blockout dates, so you can pick the right Saturday
        weeks out instead of guessing.</li>
      <li><strong>Your best bet today.</strong> And for multi-park days, one honest sentence
        about which of your parks is the better call. Same spine as everything above. When
        it's genuinely close, it says so instead of manufacturing a winner.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Every one of those keeps the house rules. Own-curve grading, words instead of scores, and
      silence when the data isn't sure. We're comfortable telling you what's coming because
      shipping is a habit here. Lanyard's 1.0, 1.1, and Crowd Intelligence all landed inside a
      single summer.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="chapter">
    <p class="chapter__kicker">The line we don't cross</p>
    <h2>What this will never be</h2>
    <p>
      No phone tracking, ever. The reading comes from what the parks publish, not from watching
      you, and your location never leaves your device. No crowd-sourced voting, no vibes, no
      subjective impressions. And no dashboard. Lanyard is a window onto a place you love that
      happens to be rigorously correct, and one honest word is what the window needs.
    </p>
    <p>
      <a href="/details">&larr; More of the details</a>
    </p>
  </section>
</DetailLayout>
